The Arena Group Holdings Inc. is a small publicly traded=C2=A0media company=
 that owns titles including TheStreet, Parade and Men=E2=80=99s Journal. Si=
nce 2019, it has also published Sports Illustrated, though it doesn=E2=80=
=99t own it: The Sports Illustrated brand is owned by a thing called Authen=
tic Brands Group, which acquired it in 2019 and then licensed it to Arena f=
or 10 years.
  [1]
=C2=A0So Arena =E2=80=9Cowns=E2=80=9D the magazine; it employs the people w=
ho write and publish it and runs its website. But Authentic owns the =E2=80=
=9CSports Illustrated=E2=80=9D brand and its intellectual property, and Are=
na pays Authentic some rent for the rights to use the name. The rent is $15=
 million per year.
  [2]

As of last summer, Arena had an equity market capitalization of around $100=
 million. Its chief executive officer was Ross Levinsohn, a longtime media =
executive, and about 40% of its stock=C2=A0was owned by affiliates of=C2=A0=
B. Riley Financial Inc., a financial services firm that has come up around =
here before. B. Riley also owned most of Arena=E2=80=99s debt, in the form =
of=C2=A0$110 million of bonds.
And then in August Arena signed a letter of intent to merge with a company =
called Simplify Inventions LLC, which was founded and run by=C2=A0Manoj Bha=
rgava, =E2=80=9Cfounder of 5-hour ENERGY,=E2=80=9D the caffeine=C2=A0shot o=
r whatever. The deal was sort of complicated: Simplify and Bhargava would n=
ot just buy Arena, but would instead merge some of their media assets (=E2=
=80=9Cthe video programming, distribution, and production assets of Bridge =
Media Networks, including its two 24-hour networks, NEWSnet and Sports News=
 Highlights, as well as the automotive and travel properties Driven and Tra=
velHost=E2=80=9D) with Arena, invest $50 million of cash, and commit to buy=
 $60 million worth of advertising over five years for =E2=80=9Ca group of c=
onsumer brands also owned by Simplify, including 5-hour ENERGY.=E2=80=9D In=
 exchange for the assets, cash and advertising, Bhargava would get control =
of Arena.
On Nov. 5, they signed a merger agreement for the deal; under the agreement=
, Bhargava (through Simplify and 5-Hour International Corp.) would end up o=
wning about 65% of the post-merger company. The $50 million cash investment=
 would partly buy common stock at a stock price of $5 per share, a premium =
to the stock price ($3.86) at the time. The merger hasn=E2=80=99t closed ye=
t, though; in particular, Arena=E2=80=99s shareholders have to vote on the =
deal before it can close, and Arena hasn=E2=80=99t yet filed the proxy stat=
ement for that vote.
But then Bhargava =E2=80=A6=C2=A0got antsy? I don=E2=80=99t know. On Nov. 3=
0, he bought all of B. Riley=E2=80=99s Arena stock and bonds, paying about =
$27.3 million ($2.90 per share) for the stock and about $78.8 million (70 c=
ents on the dollar) for the bonds. The stock closed at $2.32 that day, so B=
hargava was paying a premium for the stock; the bonds don=E2=80=99t trade =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0B. Riley owned them all =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it, uh, seems fai=
r to say he paid a premium for them too.=C2=A0At this point he became effec=
tively the controlling shareholder of Arena, with about 44% of the stock. A=
nd on Dec. 1, in connection with that purchase, two B. Riley-appointed dire=
ctors stepped down from Arena=E2=80=99s board and were replaced by two Bhar=
gava-appointed directors.
The result was that Bhargava (1) has a pending merger agreement to acquire =
Arena but also (2) already bought a controlling stake in the company and ki=
nd of took it over? Before the merger closed? Arena then quickly fired seve=
ral top executives,  including Levinsohn (though he remained chairman of th=
e board?), =E2=80=9Cto improve the operational efficiency and revenue of th=
e company.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And on Dec. 11, the board=C2=A0made Bhargava CEO:

On December 11, 2023, the board of directors (the =E2=80=9CBoard=E2=80=9D) =
of The Arena Group Holdings, Inc. (the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D) appointed=
 Manoj Bhargava as the Company=E2=80=99s Interim Chief Executive Officer, e=
ffective immediately.
Mr. Bhargava, 70, is the Founder of Innovation Ventures LLC and has served =
as its Chief Executive Officer since its inception in 2000. Mr. Bhargava ha=
s extensive management, operations and marketing experience, which he has a=
pplied to numerous new business start-ups including a water filtration comp=
any, a research and development company and an investment company.

This is just a very weird procedure! Ordinarily, if you sign a merger agree=
ment, and it=E2=80=99s conditioned on a shareholder vote, you wait until th=
e shareholders vote and the deal closes before you take over the company. B=
hargava managed to take over the company before the merger closed.
And then, uh, Arena decided to stop paying its debts? Conveniently=C2=A0mos=
t=C2=A0of Arena=E2=80=99s debt was owed to Bhargava, and it stopped paying =
that: =E2=80=9COn December 29, 2023, the Company failed to make the interes=
t payment due on the [notes] =E2=80=A6 held by Renew Group Private Limited=
=E2=80=9D; Renew is a Bhargava vehicle that bought the $110 million of bond=
s from B. Riley.
  [3]
 =E2=80=9CThe Company is currently in discussions with RGPL to restructure =
and/or amend the RGPL Notes,=E2=80=9D it said. RGPL is owned by Bhargava, a=
nd Arena=E2=80=99s CEO was also Bhargava, making those discussions sort of =
awkward. To alleviate the awkwardness, =E2=80=9Con January 4, 2024, the Boa=
rd of Directors of the Company (the =E2=80=98Board=E2=80=99) accepted the r=
esignation of Manoj Bhargava from his position as interim Chief Executive O=
fficer effective immediately. Mr. Bhargava stepped down from this role to a=
void any conflicts of interest which may arise as part of the pending trans=
actions with affiliates of Mr. Bhargava.=E2=80=9D His replacement appears t=
o be, not a new CEO, but a new Chief Business Transformation Officer appoin=
ted from FTI Consulting Inc., =E2=80=9Ca financial restructuring firm accep=
table to RGPL.=E2=80=9D
Also, though, =E2=80=9Con January 2, 2024, the Company failed to make a qua=
rterly payment due to Authentic Brands Group (=E2=80=98ABG=E2=80=99) of app=
roximately $3,750,000,=E2=80=9D the quarterly rent for the Sports Illustrat=
ed brand. And so Authentic terminated the license:
On January 18, 2024, ABG notified the Company of its intention to terminate=
 the Licensing Agreement, effective immediately, in accordance with its rig=
hts under the Licensing Agreement. Upon such termination, a fee of $45 mill=
ion became immediately due and payable by the Company to ABG pursuant to th=
e terms and conditions of the Licensing Agreement. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0The Compa=
ny is engaging in continuing discussions with ABG regarding the Licensing A=
greement.
And on Friday Arena laid off the entire staff of Sports Illustrated, which =
it apparently can no longer publish. Authentic is looking for a new publish=
er, saying: =E2=80=9CWe are committed to ensuring that the traditional ad s=
upported Sports Illustrated media pillar has best in class stewardship to p=
reserve the complete integrity of the brand=E2=80=99s legacy.=E2=80=9D
Levinsohn  apparently resigned from Arena=E2=80=99s board on Friday, saying=
 =E2=80=9CThe actions of this Board and the actions against Sports Illustra=
ted's storied brand and newsroom are the last straw.=E2=80=9D
  [4]
=C2=A0Arena=E2=80=99s stock closed below a dollar yesterday, for a market c=
ap of around $20 million.=C2=A0
I say that Arena decided to stop paying its debts, but it was perhaps not q=
uite voluntary. Arena  had about $7.3 million of cash at the end of Septemb=
er, and was losing about $5 million a month.=C2=A0In mid-November, it said =
that it had =E2=80=9Csubstantial doubt about the Company=E2=80=99s ability =
to continue as a going concern,=E2=80=9D and that it was counting on the me=
rger deal with Simplify to rescue it.=C2=A0
A  lot has been  written about the sad possible demise of Sports Illustrate=
d, but I just want to say what a weird merger this is? Bhargava somehow bou=
ght Arena twice: He agreed in August to contribute about $110 million of ca=
sh and advertising, and some television assets, for a majority stake in Are=
na, and then again in November he paid about $106 million of cash to buy a =
controlling share of Arena=E2=80=99s stock and bonds. (The first deal =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the merger =E2=80=94=C2=A0hasn=E2=80=99t closed yet, and I supp=
ose there is some doubt that it will, but there is a merger agreement anywa=
y.)
And then he made himself CEO for about three weeks, and in that time he fir=
ed the executives, put the company into default on its debt (to him?), and =
stopped paying the rent on its main asset,=C2=A0the right to publish Sports=
 Illustrated, causing that asset to disappear (and turn into a $45 million =
debt).=C2=A0And now all of Arena=E2=80=99s stock is worth less than $20 mil=
lion, and it sure looks like Bhargava overpaid. Twice?=C2=A0

