   =20
      Bitcoin ETFs
   =20
 =20

There is a well-known strategy, in financial markets, of trading ahead of i=
ndex rebalances. The idea is: You know that on Date X, Stock Y will join In=
dex Z. You know that a lot of index funds are indexed to Index Z, and they =
will have no choice but to buy Stock Y on Date X. So you buy Stock Y=C2=A0b=
efore=C2=A0Date X, knowing that you will have someone to sell it to on Date=
 X. Joining the index will bring in a whole new source of demand for the st=
ock: not just people who have looked at the stock and decided they like it,=
 but a new class of fundamentals-insensitive passive investor who will buy =
it just because it is in the index. So you buy it first, to sell to them.
There are ways for this to go wrong.=C2=A0You could get the stocks or weigh=
tings wrong, for one thing, or the trade could just get too crowded: If ind=
ex funds will need to buy $100 million of Stock Y on Date X, and 10 differe=
nt hedge funds each say =E2=80=9Cah I know that there=E2=80=99ll be $100 mi=
llion of demand for Stock Y, so I=E2=80=99ll buy $50 million of it now,=E2=
=80=9D then there=E2=80=99s $500 million of supply for $100 million of dema=
nd and the price will go down on Date X.
Or I suppose you could mess up by miscounting the number of indexed investo=
rs. You could say =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s $10 billion of assets indexed to=
 Index Z, and Stock Y=C2=A0will be 1% of the index, so that=E2=80=99s $100 =
million of demand,=E2=80=9D but if you=E2=80=99re wrong and there=E2=80=99s=
 only $5 billion of assets indexed to Index Z then there=E2=80=99ll be less=
 demand than you think. This does not seem like a major source of error. Pe=
ople have a decent idea of how much money is in, like, S&P 500 index funds.
One way to think about the launch of spot Bitcoin exchange-traded funds is =
that they were a sort of blind index add. Spot Bitcoin ETFs are, as it were=
, a way to add a new asset =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bitcoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0to the men=
u of things that you can buy on the stock exchange. It was widely expected =
that this would bring in a whole new source of demand for Bitcoin: a new cl=
ass of crypto-curious-but-not-that-curious investor who will buy Bitcoin if=
 it is a stock but not if it is anything else. (A decentralized cryptocurre=
ncy, for instance.) Turning Bitcoin into a stock, via spot Bitcoin ETFs, wo=
uld bring in those investors. So you buy Bitcoin first, to sell it to them.
It was pretty well understood for months that Bitcoin ETFs were coming, and=
 when. Everyone kind of knew that the US Securities and Exchange Commission=
 would approve them Jan. 10, and they=E2=80=99d launch the next day, to the=
 point that   someone trolled the SEC by falsely tweeting out its approval =
one day early. And so anyone who might want to do this trade had a pretty g=
ood idea about its mechanics and timing.
But it was much harder to know its=C2=A0size. How many people want to buy B=
itcoins on the stock exchange, and how much? If you are a crypto skeptic, y=
ou might guess =E2=80=9Cnobody=E2=80=9D and not do this trade. If you are a=
 crypto maximalist, you might also guess =E2=80=9Cnobody=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0you might say =E2=80=9Ccrypto is such a good alternative financial sy=
stem that it would be insane for anyone to buy it wrapped in a traditional =
stock market product provided by a big asset manager=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but=20


that=E2=80=99s kind of extreme. If you are a crypto enthusiast, though, you=
 might guess =E2=80=9Ceverybody will buy tons of Bitcoins once that becomes=
 convenient, so I should buy tons of Bitcoins to sell to them.=E2=80=9D A l=
ot of people apparently=C2=A0had that thought process, and Bitcoin soared f=
rom about $27,000 in mid-October to about $47,000 on Jan. 8.
But the actual answer seems to have been =E2=80=9Cmeh, some people, but not=
 in huge size,=E2=80=9D and Bitcoin has gone back down. The  Financial Time=
s reports:

Bitcoin has lost 16 per cent of its value over the past two weeks, as some =
investors use the much-hyped launch of bitcoin exchange traded funds earlie=
r this month to take profits and exit their holdings of the volatile crypto=
currency.
The price of bitcoin sank as much as 3 per cent on Tuesday, falling below $=
39,000 for the first time since early December.
The recent losses have unwound part of a huge rally late last year, which c=
ame amid fevered speculation that the launch of mainstream stock market fun=
ds tracking the world=E2=80=99s leading crypto token would draw in new inve=
stors to bitcoin.
But the flows into the ETFs =E2=80=94 many launched by big Wall Street play=
ers such as BlackRock =E2=80=94 have underwhelmed and investors who bought =
them have been left with hefty losses.
The 10 new funds launched on January 11, after they were approved by the US=
 Securities and Exchange Commission, had collectively pulled in $4.7bn by t=
he end of Tuesday, according to crypto investment group CoinShares. Bitcoin=
 traded at $46,100 on the day the ETFs were launched, but has fallen steadi=
ly since.
At the same time, $3.4bn has left Grayscale=E2=80=99s fund, the world=E2=80=
=99s largest bitcoin investment vehicle, since it converted to an ETF along=
side the new launches.

That=E2=80=99s $1.4 billion of net new demand. Coinmarketcap  tells me that=
 the total market capitalization of Bitcoin is about $775 billion, and it t=
rades about $30=C2=A0billion a day, so adding $1.4 billion just isn=E2=80=
=99t that much. It turns out that crypto enthusiasts anticipated much highe=
r mainstream demand for Bitcoin ETFs than has so far manifested. Which I gu=
ess is psychologically understandable. If you like Bitcoin, you might expec=
t other people to like it too, more than they actually do.
Still this is sort of a boring outcome. The much funnier outcome would be i=
f the demand for Bitcoin ETFs =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, rather, the demand for Bit=
coin from Bitcoin ETF investors =E2=80=94 was=C2=A0negative. We   talked la=
st week about one way that could happen: The Grayscale Bitcoin Trust=C2=A0w=
as=C2=A0a $29 billion pot of Bitcoins that had been locked up for years; in=
vestors could sell each other their Grayscale shares (at a discount to net =
asset value) but could not withdraw money (or Bitcoins) from the fund. But =
on Jan. 11 it converted to an ETF like everyone else. Which meant that peop=
le could withdraw from the fund, and they did: About $3.4 billion has left.=
 That=E2=80=99s less than what has gone into the other funds, but it=C2=A0c=
ould have=C2=A0been more. I wrote: =E2=80=9CIt is=C2=A0possible=C2=A0that t=
he=C2=A0main=C2=A0effect of the launch of spot Bitcoin ETFs would be people=
 taking money=C2=A0out=C2=A0of GBTC =E2=80=94 which they have never been ab=
le to do before =E2=80=94 rather than putting money=C2=A0into=C2=A0GBTC or =
the other ETFs.=E2=80=9D And the FT says:
=E2=80=9CETFs bring liquidity, and while they enable people to come in, the=
y also enable people to exit,=E2=80=9D said Varun Paul, director of market =
infrastructure at blockchain platform Fireblocks. =E2=80=9CSome investors a=
re exiting positions after buying bitcoin a long time ago, so they=E2=80=99=
re in the money.=E2=80=9D
It turns out that there was a little more demand to get in than to get out,=
 but only a little.
By the way, here=E2=80=99s another way for the demand to be negative. If yo=
u are a crypto skeptic, you might want to=C2=A0short=C2=A0Bitcoin, bet agai=
nst it. But you probably won=E2=80=99t actually do that: Shorting Bitcoin w=
ould involve going to some crypto lending platform, setting up a wallet, bo=
rrowing Bitcoins, selling them (for stablecoins?), converting into dollars,=
 and generally managing the collateral of that position in a very crypto wo=
rld. If you=E2=80=99re a crypto skeptic, you don=E2=80=99t want to live in =
the crypto world at all; shorting Bitcoin requires too much engagement with=
 Bitcoin, and you might avoid it.
On the other hand, if there are traditional financial products that allow y=
ou to bet against Bitcoin without touching any Bitcoins, well, you might do=
 that. When Bitcoin futures were introduced =E2=80=94=C2=A0products that tr=
ade on traditional regulated exchanges and that allow big investors to bet =
on or against Bitcoin without touching actual Bitcoins =E2=80=94=C2=A0there=
 was  some anticipation that they would lead to a  lot of shorting by crypt=
o skeptics, but those futures are not really a retail product. Now if you w=
ant to bet against Bitcoin you can do it in your brokerage account, by shor=
ting Bitcoin ETFs,  which is a lot easier for a crypto skeptic than actuall=
y shorting Bitcoin.=C2=A0
Oh also here=E2=80=99s this, from  the Financial Times last week:

US asset managers are vying to=E2=80=89launch exchange traded funds with le=
veraged bitcoin exposure and expand into bitcoin-based options and other cr=
yptocurrencies after last week=E2=80=99s Securities and Exchange Commission=
 approval of 11 spot bitcoin ETFs.
ProShares this week disclosed plans to launch five ETFs, including one that=
 would offer twice the daily exposure to a bitcoin-tracking index and other=
s to provide inverse bitcoin returns, paying out up to double any decline i=
n an underlying index, according to filings with the SEC. The extra leverag=
e in the ETFs =E2=80=94 which are not designed to be long-term investments =
=E2=80=94 would amplify swings experienced by the already volatile bitcoin =
price.

If you want to make a 2x levered bet against Bitcoin, soon there might be a=
n ETF for that.

