<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a well-known strategy, in financial m=
arkets, of trading ahead of index rebalances. The idea is: You know that on=
 Date X, Stock Y will join Index Z. You know that a lot of index funds are =
indexed to Index Z, and they will have no choice but to buy Stock Y on Date=
 X. So you buy Stock Y=C2=A0<em>before=C2=A0</em>Date X, knowing that you w=
ill have someone to sell it to on Date X. Joining the index will bring in a=
 whole new source of demand for the stock: not just people who have looked =
at the stock and decided they like it, but a new class of fundamentals-inse=
nsitive passive investor who will buy it just because it is in the index. S=
o you buy it first, to sell to them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are ways for this to go wrong.=C2=A0You =
could get the stocks or weightings wrong, for one thing, or the trade could=
 just get too crowded: If index funds will need to buy $100 million of Stoc=
k Y on Date X, and 10 different hedge funds each say =E2=80=9Cah I know tha=
t there=E2=80=99ll be $100 million of demand for Stock Y, so I=E2=80=99ll b=
uy $50 million of it now,=E2=80=9D then there=E2=80=99s $500 million of sup=
ply for $100 million of demand and the price will go down on Date X.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or I suppose you could mess up by miscounting =
the number of indexed investors. You could say =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s $10=
 billion of assets indexed to Index Z, and Stock Y=C2=A0will be 1% of the i=
ndex, so that=E2=80=99s $100 million of demand,=E2=80=9D but if you=E2=80=
=99re wrong and there=E2=80=99s only $5 billion of assets indexed to Index =
Z then there=E2=80=99ll be less demand than you think. This does not seem l=
ike a major source of error. People have a decent idea of how much money is=
 in, like, S&amp;P 500 index funds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to think about the launch of spot Bitc=
oin exchange-traded funds is that they were a sort of blind index add. Spot=
 Bitcoin ETFs are, as it were, a way to add a new asset =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bitc=
oin =E2=80=94=C2=A0to the menu of things that you can buy on the stock exch=
ange. It was widely expected that this would bring in a whole new source of=
 demand for Bitcoin: a new class of crypto-curious-but-not-<em>that-</em>cu=
rious investor who will buy Bitcoin if it is a stock but not if it is anyth=
ing else. (A decentralized cryptocurrency, for instance.) Turning Bitcoin i=
nto a stock, via spot Bitcoin ETFs, would bring in those investors. So you =
buy Bitcoin first, to sell it to them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It was pretty well understood for months that =
Bitcoin ETFs were coming, and when. Everyone kind of knew that the US Secur=
ities and Exchange Commission would approve them Jan. 10, and they=E2=80=99=
d launch the next day, to the point that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/34098266.257404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
cGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMTAvdGhlLXNlYy1nb3QtdHJvbGxlZC1vbi1iaXRjb2l=
